Marry forsooth, because that Men, when they marry, become but half men: 
And the other half goes to their Wives. And therefore she is called Woman; 
where before she was called but Maid.

And this of mine.---The thought of me rest with you. And hear you Doctor; 
I prithee procure me some young Fellow, that can write: For I am so troubled with Letters, 
that I neither read nor answer---

There she lies Sir, by the name of Mistress Tryman; a rich young Cornish Widow; 
though she was born in Clearken-well; and was never half a days Journey from Bride 
well in her life. Her Father was a Pinn-maker---

I thank you Sir, for your Courtly and Gentleman-like instructions, and wish you grace to follow them: 
I have seen too fearful an example lately in my neighbour Crasy, whose steps I list not trace; 
nor lend my Money to be laughed at among my Neighbours. Fare you well Sir.---

I most entirely thank you for him. And I do beseech you make yourselves no strangers 
to my poor house. We are alone; can give but light entertainment, my Daughter and I; 
since my Son Crasies misfortune drave him from us---

good wits; but away. Come your ways hither, good man; Put off your hat; Make a leg; 
Look simply. Why so! Push, ne'er tell me: He will make a rare Citizen. I have Jewels 
for you to carry to the Prince.

I cry you mercy Sir. Upon my troth, I took you for Mr. Sarpego, my learned Tutor. 
He is very like him; Is he not Gentlemen? But now I come to myself again; 
I remember this was never his walk, nor these his clothes.

That Lady Ticket is a cunning creature. I have been inward with her; 
And such are my private Intelligences, that if equal courtesy might recompense, 
I could unshale a plot is upon you.

I apprehend you Sir. Bring her to me; lodge her with me; 
    I will call you Cousin I. 
Is she very rich? At a near neighbours, said you,---Not she at Mr. Wolsies, is it?

